"Gatter W.","Timing and patterns of visible autumn migration: can effects of global warming be detected? [Zugzeiten und Zugmuster im Herbst: Einfluß des Treibhauseffekts auf den Vogelzug?]",1992,"Journal of Ornithology","133","4",,"427","436",,,10.1007/BF01640470,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0027067291&partnerID=40&md5=6a86cd37402a2721fcae385a42c76753","Aus der Station Randecker Maar, Vogelzug - Insektenwanderungen mit Forderung des Naturschutzbund Deutschland (DBV) Landesverband, des Landes Baden-Württemberg und des Forschungsfonds der DO-G, Germany","Gatter, W., Aus der Station Randecker Maar, Vogelzug - Insektenwanderungen mit Forderung des Naturschutzbund Deutschland (DBV) Landesverband, des Landes Baden-Württemberg und des Forschungsfonds der DO-G, Germany","For 21 years, diurnal migration of 46 bird species was observed under standardized conditions at Randecker Maar, SW Germany. The data are examined as to whether changes in median dates of passage of these species can be detected. For this purpose the data were analysed separately for three periods, i. e. 1970-76, 1977-83 and 1984-90. In 1970 to 1983, according to meteorological data the weather-related onset of autumn was delayed by five days in northern Germany and by six days in southern Germany. During the last observation period, 19 (67 %) of the 28 passerine short-distance migrants passed on average up to 10 days later compared to the first observation period. In 14 of these species the median dates changed continuously. Only 5 species migrated earlier than before. The majority of the short-distance migrants, therefore, seems to have adapted to the later onset of autumn. Currently there seem to be no plausible reasons for delayed migration other than climatic changes. The median dates in Non-Passerines were less clear-cut. Among short-distance migrants, delayed migration was found in 5, advanced migration in 4 species and among long-distance migrants, delayed migration was noted in 4 species, advanced migration in 3 species. Short-distance migrants may gain advantages from a longer stay on their Central European breeding grounds. Populations departing late should tend to become resident, thus advancing the median date for the fractions of population still migrating. Even advanced migration may thus be explained by global warming. Long-distance migrants, however, may only occasionally profit from a longer stay on their breeding grounds. Their arrival south of the Sahara coinciding with the short monsoon rainfalls probably has greater selective significance. Deviations in arrival times caused by climatic changes may thus lead to catastrophies as is currently discussed in the case of Tawny Pipit. The influence of global warming on bird migration and the changes in migration patterns ensuing from it were to be expected after laboratory results. Here, this influence is shown in a long-term study of free-living populations of a large number of species. © 1992 Verlag der Deutschen Ornithologen-Gesellschaft.",,"autumn; bird; global warming; migration; pipit; tawny pipit; Germany, Randecker Maar; Anthus campestris",,,,,,"Boer, M.M., Koster, E.A., Lundberg, H., Greenhouse impact in Fennoscandia — preliminary findings in a European workshop on the effects of climatic change (1990) Ambio, 19, pp. 2-10; Berthold, P., Die Vogelwelt Mitteleuropas: Entstehung der Diversität, gegenwärtige Veränderungen und Aspekte der zukünftigen Entwicklung (1990) Verh. Dtsch. Zool. Ges., 83, pp. 227-244; Ders. (1990 b): Patterns of avian migrations in light of current global „green house“ effects: A central European perspective. Acta XX Congr. Int. Orn. 780–786Berthold, P., Wiltschko, W., Mildenberger, H., Querner, U., Genetic transmission of migratory behavior into a nonmigrating bird population (1990) Experientia, 46, pp. 107-108; Bundesministerium ELF (1991): Waldzustandsbericht. BonnCrutzen, P. J., & M. Müller (1989): Das Ende des blauen Planeten? MünchenDobson, A., Jolly, A., Rubinstein, D., The greenhouse effect and biological diversity (1989) Tree, 4, pp. 64-68; Frenzel, B., (1988) Klimasituation und Klimaabläufe: Bisherige Resultate der terrestrischen Paläoklimatologie. Akad. Wissensch. und Literatur. Jb. 1988, , Wiesbaden, Stuttgart; Gatter, W., Der Brachpieper (Anthus campestris) in Baden-Württemberg (1970) Vogelwelt, 91, pp. 1-11; Gatter, W., Zugverhalten und Überwinterung von paläarktischen Vögeln in Liberia (Westafrika) (1987) Verh. orn. Ges. Bayern, 24, pp. 479-508; Gatter, W., Vogelzug in Westafrika: Beobachtungen und Hypothesen zu Zugstrategien und Wanderrouten. Vogelzug in Liberia, Teil II (1987) Vogelwarte, 34, pp. 80-92; Gatter, W., Gedehnte Zugzeiten bei Langstreckenziehern als Anpassung an die Saharaquerung (1990) Vogelwelt, 111, pp. 166-172; Gatter, W., Bewertung und Vergleichbarkeit von Medianwerten des Wegzugs am Beispiel Randecker Maar-Programm (1991) Vogelwarte, 36, pp. 19-34; Gatter, W., Gardner, R., Penski, K., Abnahme ziehender Ringeltauben Columba palumbus in Süddeutschland (1990) Vogelwelt, 111, pp. 111-116; Klafs, G., & J. Stübs (1987): Die Vogelwelt Mecklenburgs. JenaLefranc, N., La Pie-grieche a poitrine rose dans le nord-est de la France. Fluctuations, Statut actuel, notes sur la reproduction (1970) Oiseau, 40, pp. 89-103; Merikallio, E. (1951): Der Einfluß der letzten Wärmeperiode (1930–1949) auf die Vogelfauna Nordfinnlands. Proc. Xth Int. Orn. Congr. Uppsala 1950: 484–493Morel, G., The Sahel Zone as an environment for Palaearctic migrants (1973) Ibis, 115, pp. 413-417; Niebuhr, O., Greve, K., Vom Brachpieper zwischen Harz und Nordheide (1961) Orn. Mitt., 13, pp. 101-108; Niehuis, M., Ein Beitrag zum Vorkommen des Schwarzstirnwürgers —Lanius minor (1969) Mainz. Naturw. Arch., 8, pp. 333-346; Pearson, D.J., Backhurst, G.C., The southward migration of Palaearctic landbirds over Ngulia, Kenya (1976) Ibis, 118, pp. 78-105; Peitzmeier, J., Neue Beobachtungen über Klimaschwankungen und Bestandesschwank